@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
Cli's "Rename" command is not too useful when more than a few files needs to be
renamed. Let's consider practical situation: There are hundred animation
frames. Each frame is named "Animation001.jpg", "Animation002.jpg", ... You
need all frames to be copied to MS-dos disk. But Crossdos gives every file the
same name "ANIMATIO.JPG". So before copying them you have to make all the names
shorter. You can type "Rename" command hundred times, or just enter:

        EName Amination???.jpg Anim[ation]???.jpg

to rename the files to "Anim001.jpg", "Anim002.jpg", ...

Ename is not replacement for C:Rename command. This is a new Cli command, which
helps renaming groups of files.

Features:

-) Uses system's patterns to select source files.

-) Simple and powerful <new name> creation syntax.

-) Fixes problem of renaming files to files that already exist. E.g.: There are
two files: "foo" and "foo.bak". One wants to add suffix ".bak" to each of these
files. Renaming "foo" file first would cause an error, because "foo.bak"
already exists. Ename renames in proper order, so this error will newer occur.

-) Possibility of changing case of names ( to upper case or lower case ).

-) Pure. Can be made resident.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
Ename is a CLI command. So the only action you have to do is to copy it to C:
drawer. This guide placed in HELP: drawer may also come useful.

EName can be handled quite easyly from CLI, but including it to your file
manager is even more convenient.

@{u}File Master 3.0@{uu}

Enter config -> commands, click on the empty button. Enter "EName {O} TO {r,
EName string}" as a command (of cource without "" ). As a label insert "EName".
"Window" set to "Yes", "CD" and "Rescan" set to "Source". That's all.

Usage: select files you want to rename, click on EName. When "EName string"
requester appears, enter @{i}format string@{ui} (see @{"Usage" link "Usage" 0}).
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
Ename is CLI command. Its template is:

Ename FILES/A/M,FORM=AS/A,SIM=SIMULATE/S,DIR/S,UC=UPPERCASE/S,LC=LOWERCASE/S

@{b}FILES@{ub}

This parameter is required. You can enter more than one file. Wildcards are
allowed.

@{b}FORM@{ub}

This parameter is required. This is the format string. It describes how files
should be renamed.

With the syntax of format string you can use part of an old file name to create
a new one, you can paste a new text in any part of an old file name. To
construct format string use the following expressions:

-) #?. The synonym for #? is *. It pastes any number ( or 0 ) of characters
from an old file name to a new one. If there is a string surrounded by [] or
without brackets following #? it is used as a stop string. This expression
pastes part of an old file name up to stop string, or up to the end if there is
no stop string. See @{"examples" link "examples" 0}.

-) ?. Copy one character from an old file name. This expression can not stop #?
or *. See @{"examples" link "examples" 0}.

-) [text] - text surrounded by [] brackets. Omit this part of an old file name
when creating new one. It can stop #? or *. See @{"examples" link "examples" 0}.

-) (text) - text surrounded by () brackets. Insert text into a new file name.
It can not stop #? or *. See @{"examples" link "examples" 0}.

-) text without brackets. Insert the given text if it matches an old file name.
It can stop #? or *. See @{"examples" link "examples" 0}.

The @{"examples" link "examples" 0} explain it more clearly.

@{b}SIM@{ub}

When this parameter is set, files are not renamed. Only the output is
processed. This is useful to check if the format string does the right job.

@{b}DIR@{ub}

Rename also names of directories.

@{b}UC@{ub}

Uppercase. Change case of characters to upper. Works with the #? expression.

@{b}LC@{ub}

Lowercase. The same as above, but changes to lower case.
@endnode

@node "examples" "examples"
<EName command>

<old file name> => <new file name>

<old file name> => <new file name>



EName #? #?(.bak)

foo      => foo.bak

foo.bak  => foo.bak.bak



EName #? #?(.bak) UC

foo      => FOO.bak

foo.bak  => FOO.BAK.bak



EName #?.pp #?[.pp]

foo.pp   => foo

bar.pp.a => bar



EName #? #?[foo]#?

foofoo.txt  => foo.txt

bar.foo.txt => bar..txt



EName FlyAnim#?.jpg Fly[Anim]#?.jpg

FlyAnim00.jpg  => Fly00.jpg

FlyAnim01.jpg  => Fly01.jpg



EName #?.jpg #?(.jpeg)[.jpg]

foo.jpg  => foo.jpeg

bar.JPG  => bar.jpeg



EName mod.#? [mod](mod)#?

MoD.foo  => mod.foo

MOD.bar  => mod.bar
@endnode

